    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I need help writing a rejection email. We had a candidate, Marcus, who made it all the way to the final interview for our Senior Dev role here in Austin. He's really talented and had great technical skills, but we decided to go with someone who had a bit more experience with our specific cloud architecture. I want the email to be professional and kind because he was a great guy, but we need to be firm that the decision is final. Can you draft something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey Marcus,\n\nFirst off, I want to say that your technical skills were absolutely top-tier, and it was a pleasure interviewing you. You're clearly a brilliant developer, and honestly, your ability to solve complex problems is something we admire deeply.\n\nHowever, after careful consideration, we've decided to move forward with another candidate who has a bit more specific experience with our cloud architecture. We know this is tough news, especially since you were such a strong fit, but we need to be firm that this decision is final.\n\nWe truly appreciate your time and interest in joining us here in Austin. We hope you understand that we've made our choice based on the specific needs of the role at this moment.\n\nBest regards,\n\n[Your Name]\nHiring Manager\n\n***\n\n**Note:** I noticed you mentioned \"final\" three times in that draft. While that's good for clarity, it might be a bit too blunt for a rejection email. You might want to soften that last sentence slightly to \"this decision is final\" or \"we won't be able to proceed with you further\" to keep the tone professional yet firm.\n\nAlso, I noticed you mentioned \"Austin\" in your prompt. Did you mean to include",
